data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's nothing to migrate on that front. It uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, all of which remain supported in .NET 8.

That said, raw `Thread` usage like this is a good candidate for modernization. The recommended .NET 8 approach:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration notes** (for when you do encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **removed** |
| Cancelling work | Use `CancellationToken` cooperatively |
| Timeout-based abort | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter(timeout)` |
| Emergency stop | `Environment.Exit()` or `Process.Kill()` (last resort) |

**Pattern for replacing `Thread.Abort`:**

```csharp
// Instead of thread.Abort(), use cooperative cancellation:
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

await Task.Run(() =>
{
    foreach (var step in steps)
    {
        cts.Token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // check periodically
        DoWork(step);
    }
}, cts.Token);
```

Your current code is safe to migrate as-is — no `Abort` calls to fix.
